# 🔍 Internal Port Scan Detection — Threat Hunting Scenario

**Tools Used:** Microsoft Sentinel · Microsoft Defender for Endpoint · Azure Virtual Machines · KQL · Log Analytics Workspace · MITRE ATT&CK Framework  
**Frameworks:** Threat Hunting Methodology · MITRE ATT&CK  
**Skills Demonstrated:** Proactive Threat Hunting · Network Anomaly Detection · KQL Query Writing · Log Correlation · Process & File Event Analysis

---

## 📋 Overview

The server team reported significant **network performance degradation** on older devices attached to the internal `10.0.0.0/16` network. After ruling out an external DDoS attack, the security team launched a proactive threat hunt to determine whether the slowdown was caused by internal activity — such as large file downloads or internal port scanning.

This scenario follows a structured **7-phase threat hunting methodology** and maps findings to the **MITRE ATT&CK Framework**.

---

## 🔧 Pre-Lab Setup

Before beginning, the following were provisioned and confirmed operational:

- ✅ Azure Virtual Machine created and onboarded to **Microsoft Defender for Endpoint (MDE)**
- ✅ The following PowerShell command was executed on the VM to simulate malicious port scanning activity:

```powershell
Invoke-WebRequest -Uri 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/joshmadakor1/lognpacific-public/refs/heads/main/cyber-range/entropy-gorilla/portscan.ps1' -OutFile 'C:\programdata\portscan.ps1';cmd /c powershell.exe -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File C:\programdata\portscan.ps1
```

- ✅ Logs confirmed flowing into Log Analytics Workspace from:
  - `DeviceNetworkEvents`
  - `DeviceFileEvents`
  - `DeviceProcessEvents`

> 📸 **Screenshot:** *Azure portal showing VM running + MDE device inventory confirmation*

