## Phase 4 — Investigation

### Objective
Pivot from network anomalies to process and file events to identify root cause.

**Step 4 — Correlate with process events around the time of suspicious activity:**

```kql
let VMName = "windows-target-"; // Replace with your VM name
let specificTime = datetime(2024-10-18T04:09:37.5180794Z); // Replace with your timestamp
DeviceProcessEvents
| where Timestamp between ((specificTime - 10m) .. (specificTime + 10m))
| where DeviceName == VMName
| order by Timestamp desc
| project Timestamp, FileName, InitiatingProcessCommandLine
```

> 📸 **Screenshot:** *DeviceProcessEvents results showing PowerShell execution with suspicious command-line arguments near the time of network anomaly*

**Findings:**
- PowerShell was executed on the affected host around the same time the port scanning activity began
- The `InitiatingProcessCommandLine` revealed execution of a downloaded `.ps1` script (`portscan.ps1`) from `C:\programdata\`
- This confirms the network degradation was caused by **intentional internal port scanning via a PowerShell script**

**MITRE ATT&CK Mapping:**

| Technique | ID | Evidence |
|---|---|---|
| Network Service Discovery | T1046 | Sequential failed connections across the subnet |
| PowerShell Execution | T1059.001 | portscan.ps1 executed via bypass policy |
| Ingress Tool Transfer | T1105 | Script downloaded via Invoke-WebRequest |

> 📸 **Screenshot:** *MITRE ATT&CK Navigator or framework reference showing mapped techniques*

